iThankfully Stallman isn't that important. He has done quite a bit		gopher.black	70
iof work in the field. That is unarguable. 		gopher.black	70
i		gopher.black	70
iIn political theory there is the idea of the Overton window [1].		gopher.black	70
iThere is a spectrum of political discourse from far extreme to		gopher.black	70
imoderate to far extreme in the other direction. The Overton window		gopher.black	70
irepresents the scope along this spectrum of politically acceptable		gopher.black	70
ipolicies. Notably, though, is the need for actors that exceed the		gopher.black	70
iboundaries of this window to widen it in their given direction.		gopher.black	70
iFor instance, an extreme leftist view allows for a more moderate		gopher.black	70
ileftist view to be politically acceptable. Without that extremist		gopher.black	70
iview the window will shift to the right and the moderate practice		gopher.black	70
iwill seem extreme.		gopher.black	70
i		gopher.black	70
0[1] Overton window	/Overton window	gopherpedia.com	70
i		gopher.black	70
iI think this idea is applicable to more than politics, or perhaps		gopher.black	70
imore than traditional politics. The politics of technology and		gopher.black	70
ithir place in the world has extremists and Richard Stallman is		gopher.black	70
ione. The idea that all software and hardware on a user's system		gopher.black	70
imust fit his libre definition is one such view. It enables us to		gopher.black	70
ihave more reasonable discussions about the importance of the open		gopher.black	70
isource community, of public access to code, and intellectual		gopher.black	70
iproperty in general.		gopher.black	70
i		gopher.black	70
iFor this reason I appreciate the Stallmans in the world, but not		gopher.black	70
ienough to give him a pass on other behavior. Thankfully we still		gopher.black	70
ihave plenty more assholes expanding our Overton window. We don't		gopher.black	70
ineed Stallman for that anymore.		gopher.black	70
i		gopher.black	70
iIn some cases it is difficult to separate art from artist when the		gopher.black	70
iartist does something heinous. This is most often if the art		gopher.black	70
irepresents a substantial and important cultural work, or if, as is		gopher.black	70
imore often the case, it is not an individual work but the work of		gopher.black	70
imany people. Take the Cosby Show as an example here. Do we		gopher.black	70
iwrite-off that television series because of the acts of Bill		gopher.black	70
iCosby? That unjustly punishes all of the other actors, staff, and		gopher.black	70
iproduction crews that put their work into a very good program to		gopher.black	70
ispite one man. This is a difficult ethical choice. In the case of		gopher.black	70
iRichard Stallman it was fairly simple to punish the man and ignore		gopher.black	70
ithe FSF itself 18 months ago. The choice of the board to reinstate		gopher.black	70
ihim, however, now stains the rest of them with the conscious		gopher.black	70
ichoice to value him over the harm his statements cause.		gopher.black	70
